  "text": "A structured investment planning process and a clear target of financing are fundamental prerequisites for superior pension fund performance. The minimum required yield is the return a pension fund needs to achieve on a long-term basis in order to keep its financial balance. [CITATION_1] describe that the minimum required return net of asset management costs should at least consider guaranteed interest on pension liabilities, longevity risk, accumulation of value fluctuation reserves, and administration costs (1). Since all those parameters can change over time, it might be reasonable to review this minimum yield regularly, at least on an annual basis (1) 20 • To guarantee an optimal portfolio construction process, a pension fund should have realistic expectations about the return and the volatility of its strategic asset allocation (2) 21 • Furthermore, since both the expected return of the strategic asset allocation and the minimum required yield can change over time, the two performance figures should be reviewed against each other on a regular basis (1). To achieve a long-term balance between assets and liabilities, the pension fund's expected policy return 22 must exceed (or at least be equal to)",
